    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Network metrics\n",
        "\n",
        "The following metrics can help us obtain further insights into the network structure. They are also valuable as a way to characterise the network so it can later be compared to other networks or to itself through time.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Density\n",
        "\n",
        "The density of a network refers to the proportion of existing edges over all possible edges. In a network with $n$ nodes, the total number of possible edges is $n \\times (n-1)$. A density equal to $1$ corresponds to a situation where $n \\times (n-1)$ edges are present. A network with no edges at all would have density equal to 0. We can obtain the density of the African network by running the following code:\n"
      ],
      "id": "13c0dd9c"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Calculate the edge density of the 'g_africa' graph\n",
        "# Edge density is the ratio of the number of edges to the number of possible edges\n",
        "# Loops (self-edges) are excluded from the calculation\n",
        "nx.density(g_africa)"
      ],
      "id": "de3ad909",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The edge density is approximately 0.00034, giving as an indication that the network is quite sparse, since out of all possible edges, only 0.034% are present.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Reciprocity\n",
        "\n",
        "The reciprocity in a directed network is the proportion of reciprocated connections between nodes (i.e. number of pairs of nodes with edges in both directions) from all the existing edges.\n"
      ],
      "id": "7919690a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Calculate the reciprocity of the edges in the 'g_africa' graph\n",
        "nx.reciprocity(g_africa)"
      ],
      "id": "3e3ff121",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The reciprocity of this UNdirected network is naturally 0 by definition.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Degree\n",
        "\n",
        "The degree of a node is the number of edges connected to it. The in-degree of a node in a directed network is the number of edges ending in a given node. The out-degree is the number of edges starting from a given node. The `degree_histogram()` function from `networkx` allows computing the number of nodes with a certain degree (frequency of degree) in the network. In order to visualise the results, we produce a histogram\n"
      ],
      "id": "d31742e4"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Compute frequency of each degree\n",
        "degree_hist = nx.degree_histogram(g_africa)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create the x (degree) and y (frequency) values\n",
        "degrees = range(len(degree_hist))  # Degree values\n",
        "frequency = degree_hist  # Number of nodes with each degree\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the degree distribution as a histogram\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
        "plt.bar(degrees, frequency, width=0.80, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title(\"Degree Histogram\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Degree\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Number of Nodes\")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "24f1a3c5",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "We observe that most nodes have degree 3. Nodes of degree 1 are terminal nodes. Nodes of degree 2 are relatively less common than those of degree 1 and 3. This is likely due to the method used to build the network, where all the transport nodes of degree 2 are eliminated in order to simplify the network. Beyond degree 4, it is relatively rare to find any nodes. From the histogram, we see the maximum degree observed in the network is 13. Below, we obtain the ID of the node with the maximum degree as well as the value of the degree (13).\n"
      ],
      "id": "59daaa3d"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Find the node with the maximum degree\n",
        "max_degree_node = max(g_africa.degree, key=lambda x: x[1])  # x[0] is the node, x[1] is the degree\n",
        "\n",
        "print(max_degree_node)"
      ],
      "id": "be2aa887",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "and the name of the node:\n"
      ],
      "id": "7e68f218"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Get the \"name\" attribute of the node with the maximum degree\n",
        "max_degree_node_name = g_africa.nodes[max_degree_node[0]]['agglosName']\n",
        "\n",
        "print(max_degree_node_name)"
      ],
      "id": "c87bdbe7",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Distances\n",
        "\n",
        "A path in a network between node $A$ and node $B$ is a sequence of edges joining distinct nodes, starting at node $A$ and ending at node $B$. In a **directed path** all edges follow the same direction.\n",
        "\n",
        "The path length of a path between nodes $A$ and $B$ is generally defined as the number of edges forming this path. The shortest path is the minimum count of edges present to travel from $A$ to $B$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The path length can be defined in alternative ways. For example, the path length can be defined as the sum of the weights of the edges forming a path if the edges are weighted.\n",
        "\n",
        "We can use the function `shortest_path()` to find the shortest path between a given pair of nodes. For example, between Cairo and Lagos. We store the output of the shortest path function in a list called `path` which contains the sequence of nodes in the shortest path.\n"
      ],
      "id": "b635517f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Find the corresponding nodes by their name attributes\n",
        "node_names = {data['agglosName']: node for node, data in g_africa.nodes(data=True)}\n",
        "start_node = node_names.get(\"Cairo\")\n",
        "end_node = node_names.get(\"Lagos\")\n",
        "\n",
        "path = nx.shortest_path(g_africa, source=start_node, target=end_node)"
      ],
      "id": "43d8bc6e",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "We can extract the values of this to obtain the edges, which we then use to compute the total length of the shortest path between the two cities.\n"
      ],
      "id": "0f50c38b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "path_length = nx.shortest_path_length(g_africa, source=start_node, target=end_node, weight='l')\n",
        "print(path_length)"
      ],
      "id": "ce2d99d6",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "We obtain that the shortest path is 6,084.359 km long. You can check for example on Google Maps what the distance by road is between the two cities. What do you obtain? What is the relative error between our estimation and the value from Google Maps?\n",
        "\n",
        "Of all shortest paths in a network, the longest path length is the network diameter. The diameter of the African road network is the length of the longest shortest path between any pair of nodes:\n"
      ],
      "id": "2c465fc5"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "nx.diameter(g_africa)"
      ],
      "id": "6c2758c5",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The mean distance is the average length of all shortest paths in the network. The mean distance will always be smaller or equal than the diameter. It is given by:\n"
      ],
      "id": "58da6fbc"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "nx.average_shortest_path_length(g_africa)"
      ],
      "id": "d397282f",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Centrality\n",
        "\n",
        "Centrality metrics assign scores to nodes (and sometimes also edges) according to their position within a network. These metrics can be used to identify the most influential nodes. Two important centrality metrics are (1) closeness centrality, and (2) betweenness centrality. Closeness centrality is a measure of the shortest path length between a node and all the other nodes. For a given node, it is computed as the inverse of the average shortest paths between that node and every other node in the network. A node with closeness centrality close to 1 indicates that on average the node is very close to the other nodes in the network. A closeness centrality of 0 represents an isolated node. Below we compute the closeness centrality using unweighted edges and represent the results in a histogram. The distribution looks bimodal (this means that the histogram has two frequency peaks).\n"
      ],
      "id": "369ac756"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Calculate the closeness centrality for each vertex in the 'g_africa' graph, using unweighted edges \n",
        "closeness_centrality = nx.closeness_centrality(g_africa)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Extract the centrality values (we only need the values for the histogram)\n",
        "centrality_values = list(closeness_centrality.values())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the histogram of closeness centrality\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
        "ax.hist(centrality_values, bins=50, edgecolor='black')\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('Closeness Centrality')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "b8a0f27b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Betweenness centrality is a measure of the number of shortest paths going through a node. Nodes with high values of betweenness centrality indicates that they play a very important role in the overall connectivity of the network. Betweenness can also be computed for edges. We also compute the betweenness centrality for all nodes and represent it as a histogram.\n"
      ],
      "id": "674aaef7"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Calculate the betweenness centrality for each vertex in the 'g_africa' graph, using unweighted edges \n",
        "betweenness_centrality = nx.betweenness_centrality(g_africa)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Extract the betweenness centrality values (we only need the values for the histogram)\n",
        "betweenness_values = list(betweenness_centrality.values())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the histogram of betweenness centrality\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
        "ax.hist(betweenness_values, bins=50, edgecolor='black')\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('Betweennesss centrality')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
